result.execSummary:
The defendant Susan M. Obregon was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Susan M. Obregon is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Susan M. Obregon was found guilty of Harboring/Aiding a Felon (E/F/G/H/I or unclassified felony/not life), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.47(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Credit for 55 days served if revoked.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.  This applies to all counts and financial obligations.

Obey all of the rules and regulations of supervising probation agent.
*  Pay supervision fees.
Do not possess or consume alcoholic beverages and do not have alcoholic beverages within the residence.  Do not possess or consume controlled substances, except by prescription.  Submit voluntarily to random tests of blood, breath or urine.
*  Pay fine of $400.00 and court costs including all applicable surcharges.
*  DE is ordered to submit to a DNA sample & pay DNA surcharge and notice is given.
Report to P&P on next business day.

Attorney Michael Graveley appeared for the State. DE appears in custody with Aty Brenda Van Cuick.   Clerk P. Scypta.   
MINUTES:  330 - Prior to court, Atty Van Cuick stated that a letter was sent to the court by the DE's son re: sentencing. No letter has been rec'd by the Court, the DA, or by DE's atty. No restitution requested.  Appeal rights given.
